Should you forfeit in League of Legends?¶

Joshua Schmucki

Introduction¶

League of Legends is a world-renowned free-to-play MOBA (Multiplayer Online Battle Arena) game developed by RIOT Games. Since its release in 2009, League of Legends has garnered over 100 million users and has been a driving force in bringing esports into the limelight of entertainment.

The game pits two teams of five players against each other in an effort to destroy the other team's base. The standard League of Legends map has each team's base on the opposite side of the map. Each player on a team is given a specific role which binds them to a certain area of the map called a lane. The two bases are connected via these lanes. Each lane has turrets which must be destroyed in order to get closer to the enemy's base. Each team sends their players to their respective lanes where the players will fight near the centerline of the map in their areas for gold and other resources. Picking your fights wisely and coordinating with your team will allow you to overpower your opponents and attack their towers/buildings for a short time. If you and your team continue to fight and farm resources wisely, you will eventually push closer to the enemy's base and destroy it for the win

There are many factors that contribute to a team's ability to win such as team synergy, team composition, advantages won by purchasing items with gold, etc. However, just as there are ways for a team or a player to get ahead in a game, there are methods in place for a team in a disadvantageous state to come back into a winning situation.

-Players can buy items with gold that is won by killing enemy minions (small, easy-to-kill ai soldiers that constantly push against the enemy base), towers (combat structures which fire at any hostile entity), or champions (enemy players). Items then give combat advantage through stat bonuses. Getting more/better items than your lane opponent will generally get you ahead of them.

-Besides enemy minions and enemy players, there are neutral monsters that can give a large cahce of gold, or even a buff for the player that defeats it. There are also Epic neutral monsters which usually require the combined efforts of a few team members to take down, but once defeated, they give powerful buffs to the team that defeats them. These monsters are dragons of different kinds or the biggest monster called Baron Nashor.

-Even if an opponent is much stronger than you, multiple teammates can gang up on that opponent. Doing this can even be beneficial, as players who find themselves in a strong position are automatically given a bounty which is paid out to the player that kills them. This gives the killing player a monetary boost, and disadvantage to the bountied player as their lane can be attacked with little risk to the attackers while the bountied player is respawning. It does wonders to even out a game.

Problem Statement¶

As I mentioned, there are many factors that play into a team's ability to win that change constantly throughout the game, and an early advantage will not always correlate to a later win. However, I have noticed a toxic trait among a growing number of players. As soon as there is any disadvantage for their team, however slight, some players will immediately announce to the rest of the team that the game is a lost cause, and that the entire team should give up. They may even sometimes use the enemy team's advantage to justify throwing the game by intentionally killing themselves (which gives gold to the enemy) or by quitting the game altogether (which puts the game in a 4 v 5 situation and is basically unwinnable for the 4). In essence, they would rather quickly get this game over and go onto another one instead of putting in any effort to come back from a slight disadvantage.

My Goal¶

My goal is to observe how some common conditions that players use to justify throwing or quitting affect the final outcome of the game. As a bonus, I will be teaching the principles and steps of the Data Science Pipeline along the way.

Step 1: Data Scraping¶

The first step in the Data Science Pipeline is to gather large amounts of applicable data to do some analytics on. In our case, we need to find game data from a large number of League of Legends games with timestamped events that can be counted according to the type of event and when during the game they happened. What better place to get such data than right from the source!? At The Riot Games Developer Portal, you can find an api to get data for a number of RiotGames programs. The first step is to get an API key by signing in at the home page linked above. There, you can get a developer API key for developing an application or for scraping data, or you can apply for a Product API key that will allow you to query much more often and in higher volumes. For the purposes of this project, a developer API key will be enough. This API key will be used to authenticate your requests to the Riot databases. This process can be done entirely on the developer website too with a little know how on the API page. Note: I have hidden the API key used to scrape the data in this notebook

The first step is to get information regarding a user's account. In the game and the client, players refer to each other via their summoner name. However, this is rarely how the Riot Database indexes or queries information on users. Thankfully, there is a method in the The API to get account info from a player's summoner name. Checking the api documentation, we can see that we form a query to the Riot database with a specific URL in the form

https://na1.api.riotgames.com/lol/summoner/v4/summoners/by-name/[SUMMONER NAME HERE]?api_key=[API KEY HERE]

In [5]:
def get_puuid_from_summoner(s_name):
    global number_of_requests
    global number_of_waits
    number_of_requests += 1
    while True:
        r = requests.get("https://na1.api.riotgames.com/lol/summoner/v4/summoners/by-name/" + s_name + "?api_key=" + apikey)
        if(r.status_code == 429):
            time.sleep(5)
            number_of_waits += 1
        else:
            break
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text,'html.parser')
    me = json.loads(soup.text)
    return me['puuid']

Note: all functions that query the Riot database have to be aware of the limit on the API key. Using the developer API key, queries can only

  • Request 20 times per second for a total of:
  • 100 Requests every 2 minutes

After you send a query, if you get a response code of 429, this indicates that you have gone over the rate limit for the api key. If we get this code, we will want to wait a little bit before sending another request

def get_game_ids_from_puuid(puuid, start = 0, count = 10):
    global number_of_requests
    global number_of_waits
    number_of_requests += 1
    while True:
        r = requests.get("https://americas.api.riotgames.com/lol/match/v5/matches/by-puuid/" + puuid + "/ids?start="+ str(start) + "&count=" + str(count) + "&api_key=" + apikey)
        if(r.status_code == 429):
            time.sleep(5)
            number_of_waits += 1
        else:
            break
    soup=BeautifulSoup(r.text,'html.parser')
    games = json.loads(soup.text)
    return games

Holy cow, that's a lot of data. This is a much bigger data return than anything else we've looked at so far. You are looking at summary statistics for the game that we entered. This would be information you could see in the post-game lobby scoreboard. In the 'metadata' object, there is a list of participants which is the puuid of every player in the game, and in the 'info' object, there is another participants array which has objects whose index corresponds to the user in the metadata list. These info participant objects are statistics for that particular player. Later on, we will organize this data dump so that it is much easier to look at and get rid of any extraneous metadata. Let's write another function to get this match summary from a match Id.

def get_match_data(match_id):
    global number_of_requests
    global number_of_waits
    number_of_requests += 1
    while True:
        r = requests.get("https://americas.api.riotgames.com/lol/match/v5/matches/" + match_id + "?api_key=" + apikey)
        if(r.status_code == 429):
            time.sleep(5)
            number_of_waits += 1
        else:
            break
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text,'html.parser')
    match_data = json.loads(soup.text)
    return match_data

This is even more data than before! This result is a list of 'frames' from the game. A frame is a period of about 60 seconds where events are captured and catalogued. At the beginning of each frame, each player's instantaneous statistics are captured as well. This will be extremely useful for us to examine the game state over time. Let's write another function to retrieve the timeline from a match given a match Id

In [18]:
def get_match_timeline(match_id):
    global number_of_requests
    global number_of_waits
    number_of_requests += 1
    while True:
        r = requests.get("https://americas.api.riotgames.com/lol/match/v5/matches/" + match_id + "/timeline?api_key=" + apikey)
        if(r.status_code == 429):
            time.sleep(5)
            number_of_waits += 1
        else:
            break
    soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text,'html.parser')
    timeline = json.loads(soup.text)
    return timeline

The last bit of scraping we need to do involves retrieving assets for the game. If you look through the timeline, you will see events that pertain to items (buying, selling, undoing, destroying). The name of the item is not stored with the frame, only the number. That number refers to some databases which store information about each item or champion etc. given a numeric Id. Here, I am retrieving those databases and writing functions to get a champion name and an item name given their numeric Id.

In [19]:
r = requests.get("http://ddragon.leagueoflegends.com/cdn/11.10.1/data/en_US/champion.json")

champs = json.loads(soup.text)
champion_id_dictionary = {}
for c in champs['data']:
    champion_id_dictionary[int(champs['data'][c]['key'])] = c
def get_champion(id):
    return champion_id_dictionary[id]

Tidying data¶

This is the process of taking the raw data you retrieve and make it look more presentable/readable. First implemented is a short helper function that takes an integer number of milliseconds and converts it into a string with the format (mm:ss). Most timestamps are stored as a number of milliseconds since the start of the match, so having this will help time readability

In [21]:
def ms_string(i):
    m = int((i/1000)/60)
    s = int(i/1000) - (m*60)
    return str(m) + ":" + str(s).zfill(2)

Structure¶

I found it was easiest to keep track of game data by making classes for the different components of each game.

Participant¶

A single player in a game. Specifies the players database id (puuid), champion they played this game (champ), numeric id in the game's data (num), which lane this player was in (lane), whether this player won their game, and the player's in-game name (summoner_name).

In [22]:
class Participant:
    def __init__(self, puuid, champ, num, lane, team, won, summoner_name):
        self.puuid = puuid
        self.champ = champ
        self.num = num
        self.lane = lane
        self.team = team
        self.won = won
        self.summoner_name = summoner_name
        self.has_myth = False
    def __str__(self):
        return ("Summoner Name: " + self.summoner_name + "\nChamp: " + self.champ + "\nLane: " + self.lane)

Team¶

Simply a list of players(Participants) and whether this team won or not

In [23]:
class Team:
    def __init__(self):
        self.participants = []
        self.won = False
    def add(self, participant):
        self.participants.append(participant)
        self.won = participant.won
    def lookup_champ(self, n):
        for p in self.participants:
            if(p.num == n):
                return p.champ
        return 'Champ Not Found'
    def lookup_lane(self, n):
        for p in self.participants:
            if(p.num == n):
                return p.lane
        return 'Champ Not Found'
    def __str__(self):
        ret = ""
        for p in self.participants:
            ret += p.lane + ": " + p.champ + " (" + p.summoner_name + ")\n"
        if(self.won):
            ret += "Winning Team\n"
        else:
            ret += "Losing Team\n"
        return ret

Game¶

On the highest level there is a game. A game has

-2 teams (red and blue team) with

-5 participants(players) on each team.

-Match data (cumulative stats for each player after the game has finished) and a

-Timeline (a timeline of events that happen in game).

Players are numbered 1-10 in the match and timeline data (which a player object stores), so in order to find a player's information, a game has a boolean array specifying if the player number is on the red or blue team. Then, that team can be searched for the desired player number.

A game can also be easily identified by it's duration(length).

A game can lookup a champion name or a player's name based on the player's integer number from the match or timeline data. It can also lookup which team a player is on based on that same integer number

Finally, later on, a game's timeline will be parsed for important events and stored in a dataframe (TDF)

In [24]:
class Game:
    def __init__(self, match_data, timeline):
        self.timeline = timeline
        self.match_data = match_data
        self.blue_team = Team()
        self.red_team = Team()
        self.part_on_blue = [pd.NA]
        self.length = ms_string(match_data['info']['gameDuration'])
    
    def add_participant(self, participant):
        
        if(participant.team == 100):
            self.part_on_blue.append(True)
            self.blue_team.add(participant)
        else:
            self.part_on_blue.append(False)
            self.red_team.add(participant)
    def lookup_champ(self, n):
        if n == 0:
            return 'minion'
        elif self.part_on_blue[n]:
            return self.blue_team.lookup_champ(n)
        else:
            return self.red_team.lookup_champ(n)
    def lookup_lane(self, n):
        if self.part_on_blue[n]:
            return self.blue_team.lookup_lane(n)
        else:
            return self.red_team.lookup_lane(n)
    def lookup_team(self, n):
        if self.part_on_blue[n]:
            return "Blue Team"
        return "Red Team"
    def get_new_puuid(self, pid):
        for p in self.red_team.participants:
            if(p.puuid == pid):
                return self.blue_team.participants[random.randrange(0,5)].puuid
        return self.red_team.participants[random.randrange(0,5)].puuid
    def summoner_lookup_puuid(self, puuid):
        for p in self.red_team.participants:
            if(p.puuid == puuid):
                return p.summoner_name
        for p in self.blue_team.participants:
            if(p.puuid == puuid):
                return p.summoner_name
        return(pd.NA)
    def lookup_summoner(self, summ_name):
        for p in self.red_team.participants:
            if(p.summoner_name == summ_name):
                return True
        for p in self.blue_team.participants:
            if(p.summoner_name == summ_name):
                return True
        return false
    def __repr__(self):
        ret = "Game() " + self.length
        if(self.blue_team.won):
            ret += " Blue Victory"
        else:
            ret += " Red Victory"
        return ret
    def __str__(self):
        return "Red Team:\n" + str(self.red_team) + "------------\nBlue Team:\n" + str(self.blue_team)

Tidying Timeline Data¶

The first data we will sort through is a match's timeline. The raw timeline is a long, unreadable json object with a lot of extraneous metadata. I had to decide what events to extract from the timeline object based on how important they were to the outcome of the game.

The mission of this project is to find events that a player can perceive about the enemy team that would lead them to conclude that a game is 'too far gone to win'. Based on that, I decided to only track player events that an enemy player can see.

This would exclude things like

  • when a player upgrades an ability (which a player can only see about themselves)
  • when a player places a ward (which a player cannot possibly consider during the game)

I also excluded events that don't contribute to either team or that can be inferred from other events.

  • 'PAUSE_END' (this marks when the players can take control of their characters in the very first second they load into the game)
  • 'ITEM_DESTROYED/SOLD' (You don't really care what items an enemy used to have, only the items they currently have. Also, when you construct a certain item that is comprised of other items combined, there will be a 'item_purchased' event for the resulting item and destroying the base items. You only really need to know that they now have the resulting item)

Events I have included from the timeline are ones such as

  • CHAMPION_KILL (gives the killer a monetary advantage)
  • BUILDING_KILL (gives the entire team a small monetary advantage)
  • ITEM_PURCHASED (gives the buyer a stat advantage)
  • ELITE_MONSTER_KILL (gives the entire team a stat advantage)

Below is code which takes a complete Game object and filters the game's timeline object for desired events. Eventually, it will add a new field to the Game object to store a dataframe of events, which will be much more readable

In [25]:
def process_timeline(g):
    event = [] #These are all different fields I am tracking for every event. At the end, these lists will become columns
    mstime = [] #in the resulting dataframe
    realtime = []
    desc = []
    playernum = []
    victimnum = []
    assist = []
    champ = []
    team = []
    lane = []
    
    #here, we are going to look through every frame in the game's timeline and record events that may be important to the 
    #outcome of the game
    for f in g.timeline['info']['frames']:
        ev = f['events']
        for e in ev:
            typ = e['type']
            #These are the codes for different events to be excluded
            if((typ == 'ITEM_DESTROYED') | (typ == 'SKILL_LEVEL_UP') | (typ == 'PAUSE_END') | (typ == 'WARD_PLACED') | (typ == 'WARD_KILL') | (typ == 'GAME_END') | (typ == 'ITEM_SOLD') | (typ == 'ITEM_UNDO') | (typ == 'CHAMPION_TRANSFORM')):
                continue
            #These are certain fields that all events have and we can record right away by adding them to our lists
            event.append(typ)
            mstime.append(e['timestamp'])
            realtime.append(ms_string(e['timestamp']))
            
            ##Beyond this point, we are trying to fill the rest of the columns with values from the event in question.
            ##However, some events have unique fields that other events don't have, or the fields are stored in a different
            ##format. This is my attempt at synthesizing all the different types of eventdata fields into a similar format
            ## so events can be compared
            if(typ == 'PAUSE_END'):
                playernum.append(pd.NA)
            elif((typ == 'CHAMPION_KILL') | (typ == 'CHAMPION_SPECIAL_KILL') | (typ == 'TURRET_PLATE_DESTROYED') | (typ == 'BUILDING_KILL') | (typ == 'ELITE_MONSTER_KILL')):
                playernum.append(e['killerId'])
                champ.append(g.lookup_champ(e['killerId']))
                if(e['killerId'] == 0):
                    x = e['position']['x']
                    y = e['position']['y']
                    lane.append("see_desc")
                    if(y < map_size - x):
                        team.append("Blue Team")
                    else:
                        team.append("Red Team")
                else:
                    team.append(g.lookup_team(e['killerId']))
                    lane.append(g.lookup_lane(e['killerId']))
                    
            elif((typ == 'SKILL_LEVEL_UP') | (typ == 'ITEM_PURCHASED') | (typ == 'LEVEL_UP')):
                playernum.append(e['participantId'])
                champ.append(g.lookup_champ(e['participantId']))
                lane.append(g.lookup_lane(e['participantId']))
                team.append(g.lookup_team(e['participantId']))
            elif(typ == 'DRAGON_SOUL_GIVEN'):
                playernum.append(-1)
                champ.append(pd.NA)
                lane.append(pd.NA)
                if(e['teamId'] == 100):
                    team.append("Blue Team")
                else:
                    team.append("Red Team")
            else:
                playernum.append("?")
        
            if(typ == 'PAUSE_END'):
                desc.append(pd.NA)
                victimnum.append(pd.NA)
            elif typ == 'SKILL_LEVEL_UP':
                desc.append("Skill Slot " + str(e['skillSlot']))
                victimnum.append(e['skillSlot'])
            elif typ == 'ITEM_PURCHASED':
                desc.append(get_item(e['itemId']) + " Purchased")
                victimnum.append(e['itemId'])
            elif typ == 'LEVEL_UP':
                desc.append('Level up to ' + str(e['level']))
                victimnum.append(e['level'])
            elif typ == 'CHAMPION_KILL':
                victimnum.append(e['victimId'])
                desc.append(str(e['killerId']) + " kills " + str(e['victimId']))
            elif typ == 'CHAMPION_SPECIAL_KILL':
                ret = e['killType']
                if(e['killType'] == 'KILL_MULTI'):
                    ret += " (" + str(e['multiKillLength']) + ")"
                desc.append(ret)
                victimnum.append(pd.NA)
            elif typ == 'TURRET_PLATE_DESTROYED':
                desc.append(str(e['killerId']) + ' destroys ' + e['laneType'] + ' turret plating')
                victimnum.append(e['laneType'])
            elif typ == 'ELITE_MONSTER_KILL':
                if(e['killerTeamId'] == 100):
                    ret = 'blue'
                else:
                    ret = 'red'
                desc.append(ret + ' team kills ' + e['monsterType'])
                victimnum.append(e['monsterType'])
            elif typ == 'BUILDING_KILL':
                ret = e['buildingType'] + " destroyed in " + e['laneType']
                if e['buildingType'] == 'TOWER_BUILDING':
                    ret = e['towerType'] + " " + ret
                desc.append(ret)
                victimnum.append(e['buildingType'])
            elif typ == 'DRAGON_SOUL_GIVEN':
                desc.append(e['name'])
                victimnum.append(e['teamId'])
            else:
                desc.append("UNKNOWN EVENT")
                victimnum.append(pd.NA)
            try:
                assist.append(e['assistingParticipantIds'])
            except(KeyError):
                assist.append([])
    ##Here is the creation of the dataframe we were looking to make
    df = pd.DataFrame({'Event_Code' : event, 
                       'ms_time' : mstime,
                       'in_game_time': realtime,
                       'Event_Description' : desc,
                       'Event_Actor' : playernum,
                       'Actor_Champ' : champ,
                       'Actor_Lane' : lane,
                       'Actor_Team' : team,
                       'Event_Subject' : victimnum, 
                       'Assisters' : assist})
    g.tdf = df

Now we need to make Game objects and all their subsidiary objects. This function will take a list of game Ids and create a new game object for each game Id. This function will also create team objects and fill them with participant objects which will be filled by information from the match data. In the end, it will return a list of complete Game objects.

Note that this function can be used to blindly process all the games in the gamelist, or it can be used to specifically find ranked games(explained later) in the game list and return those.

  • ranked - a boolean specifying whether or not to search for a ranked game
  • n - desired number of games to process from the gamelist
  • namelist - a list of names. Skip processing the game if any person in this list was a participant in the game

If I am looking specifically for ranked games, this method will skip processing any other match type except for ranked games. Other factors are used to weed certain games out. These are more thorougly described later in the data analysis section of the notebook

In [26]:
def process_gamelist(gamelist, ranked, n, namelist):
    no_games = 0
    matches = []
    for g in gamelist:
        ##Here, if we have reached the desired number of games processed, we will end the loop
        if((no_games == n) & ranked):
            break
        ##This is a function we made earlier to retrieve the match data from the API
        gd = get_match_data(g)
        ##This tests if the game was successfully retrieved. If the request to the API failed, the resulting game data
        ##Will not have an 'info' field. If a request fails for whatever reason, we will skip processing this game
        try:
            test = gd['info']
        except(KeyError):
            if debugging:
                print('bad_request')
            continue
        ##In the Information stored about a game, there is a field that specifies what kind of game the player queued up for
        ##A queue ID of 420 indicates that the game was a Ranked soloqueue 5v5 game (I promise I'm not making this up)
        if(ranked & (gd['info']['queueId'] != 420)):
            if debugging:
                print('not_ranked')
            continue
        ##Because of the nature of the analysis I want to do, I will skip processing a game if it was surrendered before it 
        ##ended naturally
        if((gd['info']['participants'][0]['gameEndedInEarlySurrender'] | gd['info']['participants'][0]['gameEndedInSurrender']) & ranked):
            if debugging:
                print('surrendered')
            continue
        ##Here I am checking if any member of the current game was part of a previous game that I've analyzed. If so, skip
        ##this game and go to the next one
        used = False
        if(ranked):
            for part in gd['info']['participants']:
                if part['summonerName'] in namelist:
                    if debugging:
                        print("used")
                    used = True
                    break
        if used:
            continue
        ##Here, I have accepted the game as valid according to the factors above, and am creating the Game object along with 
        ##information about everyone who played in it
        gt = get_match_timeline(g)
        game = Game(match_data = gd, timeline = gt)
        p_list = game.match_data['metadata']['participants']
        i = 1
        for p in p_list:
            c = game.match_data['info']['participants'][i-1]['championName']
            l = game.match_data['info']['participants'][i-1]['teamPosition']
            t = game.match_data['info']['participants'][i-1]['teamId']
            w = game.match_data['info']['participants'][i-1]['win']
            s = game.match_data['info']['participants'][i-1]['summonerName']
            part = Participant(puuid=p, num=i, champ=c, lane=l, team=t, won=w, summoner_name=s)
            game.add_participant(part)
            i = i+1
        process_timeline(game)
        matches.append(game)
        no_games += 1
    return matches

This is much better! We can actually see events and their contents at a glance. Now is a good time to explain the structure of the timeline dataFrame. Keep in mind that a row corresponds to one event.

  • Event_Code - Code that identifies different kinds of events. Useful when trying to find effects based on types of events
  • ms_time - milliseconds since the start of the game. Acts as a timestamp for the event
  • in_game_time - (mm::ss) format of ms_time. Useful for visualizing timestamps, not for comparison
  • Event_Description - My best effort to describe the event in english based on the event's metadata
  • Event_Actor - The number for the player who was the primary actor in the event
  • Actor_Champ - The champion played by the primary actor
  • Actor_Lane - The lane position of the primary actor
  • Actor_Team - The team that the primary actor is a part of, or the team that benefits from the event
  • Event_Subject - The item or player which the primary actor does the event to. In the case of events such as ITEM_PURCHASED, this is the numeric ID of the item bought. However, in events like CHAMPION_KILL, this column represents the player that was killed by the primary actor. For events which don't necessarily have a victim, this column is filled with NA
  • Assisters - Applicable to events which can have more than one player contributing to the completion of the event (CHAMPION_KILL, ELITE_MONSTER_KILL). Assisting in an event can sometimes have implications for the rest of the game.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that we have a way to acquire and parse data, we just have to amass some games to analyze and then look at how well the justifications of the discouraged players hold up.

Some factors that we have to consider before doing analysis:

I would like to pull a sample of 500 games to start. This will give us a wide range of games/events to choose from. I want to make this as random as possible. If I pull 500 games from the same player, that player may have faults intrinsic to their playstyle that are responsible for a winstreak/losestreak. This, I anticipate, will be hard to account for in an analysis. To minimize this effect, I will take 5 games from different players. I will start with a single name, get 5 games from that profile, then choose 1 random game and select 1 random user from the other team to sample the next 5 games. Choosing someone from the enemy team will guarantee that I don't choose the same user twice or a friend of that user (which may lead to analyzing the same matches twice if a user plays with their friends a lot).

Another stipulation is that I must take is that the matches I analyze must be ranked. I can assume (for the most part) that players will try their hardest in ranked games, resulting in 'typical' gameplay with 'typical' outcomes. People will tend to experiment with champions or strategies they are unexperienced with in non-ranked gamemodes, which can skew an outcome

Another Stipulation is that I will be polling from games around the skill level of the initial person I am polling. If you want to get 500 games from around gold/silver, make sure the first name entered corresponds to a gold/silver player. The same goes for any other rank.

Another stipulation is that I will be excluding games where either team voted to surrender early. If a team didn't let the game play out to fruition, then we cannot know if the winning team won because the game was truly lost for the surrendering team, or if a player perceived that the game was lost and threw in the towel. We need to observe the results of full games so that we can zero in on the early factors that truly influence the end game

Finally, I will only be looking at events within the first 20 minutes of a game. The goal of this analysis is to find early signs of a game 'too far gone' and should be worth surrendering. 20 minutes includes the first forefeit window at 15 minutes (which requires a unanimous vote on behalf of the team) and the normal forefeit window after 20 minutes (which requires only 4/5 players to surrender). In other words, this timeframe only includes factors that discouraged players see before forefeiting.

    i = random.randrange(0,len(gs))
    g = gs[i]
    return g.get_new_puuid(old_pid)

And just like that, we have at least 500 games that match our criteria. Now to start crunching numbers. We will compile a list of common conditions that players call early surrender justifications, then query the list of games to see if those conditions truly result in a loss.

First Blood¶

Some players are ready to throw in the towel as soon as the enemy team gets first blood. This will be an easy first test, as we just count up the number of teams that got first blood AND won and divide it by the total number of games.

In [33]:
first_blood_wins = 0
for gam in master_list:
    a = gam.tdf
    b = a[(a['Event_Code'] == 'CHAMPION_SPECIAL_KILL') & (a['Event_Description'] == 'KILL_FIRST_BLOOD')]
    fb = b.iloc[0]['Actor_Team']
    if(fb == 'Red Team'):
        w = gam.red_team.won
    else:
        w = gam.blue_team.won
    if(w):
        first_blood_wins += 1
first_blood_wins / len(master_list)
Out[33]:
0.5657370517928287

As it turns out, the team who gets first blood often has an above average expected winrate. However, I don't think it's enough of a split to definitively count the game as lost

First Dragon¶

Another point where people are ready to call it quits is when the enemy team gets the first dragon, which supplies a small stat buff to the team that kills it. Let's do a similar analysis.

We will have to change one thing. Some games, a dragon is never defeated in the duration of the game. To account for this, we must count the number of games where no dragon is defeated and subtract it from the total amount of games we are polling from, as a game with no dragons defeated doesn't contribute to the winrate of winning/losing games with a dragon defeated in them

In [34]:
first_dragon_wins = 0
no_drags = 0
for gam in master_list:
    a = gam.tdf
    b = a[(a['Event_Code'] == 'ELITE_MONSTER_KILL') & (a['Event_Subject'] == 'DRAGON')]
    try:
        fd = b.iloc[0]['Actor_Team']
        if(fd == 'Red Team'):
            w = gam.red_team.won
        else:
            w = gam.blue_team.won
        if(w):
            first_dragon_wins += 1
    except(IndexError):
        no_drags += 1
first_dragon_wins / (len(master_list) - no_drags)
Out[34]:
0.5836653386454184

Getting the first dragon provides a significantly above-average winrate. However, having a 30-40% win chance as the losing team is better than the 0% win chance that forefeiting affords.

Kill difference at 20 mins¶

Now, just doing a simple games_where_this_happens/total_games winrate analysis is somewhat simple. However, league games and their interactions tend to be more complex. First blood can just be an unfortunate accident and don't always reflect the strength of a team over time. Let's take a look at winrate based on the kill difference between the two teams at 20 minutes (around the time where teams look to surrender if at all).

First, lets look at a distribution of games and the winner's kill counts at 20 minutes. This may help inform a winrate graph by showing the sample size for games with a certain kill difference (winning team's kills - losing team's kills). We should expect to see that in most games, the team that eventually wins should have more kills than the team that eventually loses. If both teams are evenly matched (as in randomly made, rank-based matchmaking), then most games should be pretty close in kill count throughout the game. Whenever a team gets ahead in kills (and by extension gold) they will tend to win the game. In other words, you won't expect many games where the winning team has a really high kill difference if the teams are mostly evenly matched, and you wont expect the winning team to be behind in kills at the mid game.However, there will be instances where the team that eventually wins will be behind at 20 mins. This will be shown by a negative kill difference.

In [40]:
abs_diff = []
diffs = []
for gam in master_list: 
    a = gam.tdf
    b = a[a['ms_time'] <= (20 * 60 *1000)] #20*60*1000 = number of milliseconds in 20 mins
    c = b[(b['Event_Code'] == 'CHAMPION_KILL')]
    blue_kills = len(c[c['Actor_Team'] == 'Blue Team'])
    red_kills = len(c[c['Actor_Team'] == 'Red Team'])

for a_d in unique_abs_diffs:
    a_c.append(abs_diff.count(a_d))

As expected, the winning team usually has more kills (ahead by 5-10) than the losing team. However, this graph also shows that most of our data lies between -5 and 15, so calculating winrates for kill differences outside of a certain range will be doing so based on very few points.

Now, let's examine the actual winrate versus kill difference at 20 mins. This is a bit complicated, as we are looking at stats before the outcome of the game is determined. We are looking at one team's chance of doing x and eventually winning, but a game has two teams. If a team has a kill difference of 5 and wins, the other team will have a kill difference of -5 and loses. This is important because a team's kill difference is not equivalent to a win/loss for that team. A team with a negative kill difference can still win, and a team with a positivie kill difference can still lose.

The data from the graph above shows us how many teams eventually win with x kill difference, but to get the chance of winning under these circumstances, we need to divide it by the total number of teams with those circumstances. This will be the number of games with |x| = x kill difference.

$$ \frac{w} {\left(w + l\right)} $$

Where

  • w = the number of TEAMS who won while 1 kill ahead at 20 mins
  • l = the number of TEAMS who lost while 1 kill ahead at 20 mins

Which is equivalent to $$ \frac{w}{|g|} $$

Where

  • |g| = the number of GAMES with a kill difference of +/- 1

This will only really apply to games where we have examples of games won with a kill difference of x and -x, or the win chance will be 50/50. For example, take the graph above where x = 22. It shows that there is only 1 team that won with 22 kills ahead of their opponent. This also means that there is only 1 game in our data set with a kill difference of +/- 22 games. So in our data set, the number of teams who won with a kill difference of 22 is 1, and the number of teams who lost with a kill difference of 22 is 1, so according to our data, you have a 50/50 chance of winning with a kill difference of 22, which is obviously incorrect.

In [41]:
##Make a dictionary that maps the unique difference values and the number of times they occur
diff_dict = {unique_diffs[i] : c[i] for i in range(len(c))}
##Make a dictionary that maps the unique absolute difference values and the number of tiems they occur
abs_dict = {unique_abs_diffs[i] : a_c[i] for i in range(len(a_c))}
wr = []
used_diffs = []
for d in unique_diffs:##go through our list of unique kill diffs and calculate a winrate
    if (d == 0):
        used_diffs.append(d)
        wr.append(.5) #Can assume 50/50 odds for teams with no kill difference
        continue
    if (d*-1) in unique_diffs:
        used_diffs.append(d)
        wr.append(diff_dict[d] / abs_dict[abs(d)])
plt.figure(1)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.plot(used_diffs, wr)

While the line appears 'bumpy', I believe a clear correlation is shown here. As your team's kill difference begins to deviate from 0, your chance of winning will quickly deviate from 50%. As the kill difference deviates from 0 further, there are diminishing returns. Once you are 10 kills ahead in a game, you will more or less always win that game, getting one more kill won't increase your chances much more than it was before. For this reason, I believe that the graph will be a polynomial of the form

$$ \frac{ax}{\sqrt{x^2 + b}} + c $$

I know this equation looks like it came out of nowhere, but if you type an equation like this into something like Desmos, you will see that this general graph shape demonstrates the diminishing returns model I described, which I knew the equation of from experience. We now have to choose appropriate variables for a, b, and c, which we will use scipy's curve fit operations to find a good line for these points.

In [42]:
##This is a function which represents the polynomial we are trying to perfect in order to get a model for our data
def poly(x, a, b, c):
    ret = []
    for i in x:
        ret.append(((a*i) / (math.sqrt(i**2) + b) + c))
    return ret
##Here, we are using the scipy library to adjust our coefficients a,b,and c, then storing the final values
ret, _ = scip.curve_fit(poly, used_diffs, wr)
a, b, c = ret
##We want to plot our model wto see how accurate it is. We are generating a new list of x models ranging from the smallest
##x value we used in our plot from earlier to the largest x value we used
new_x = np.arange(min(used_diffs) - 1, max(used_diffs)+1, 1)
##Calculate new y values with our shiny new polynomial and our new x values
new_y = poly(new_x, a, b, c)
plt.figure(2)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.plot(new_x, new_y, '--', color='red')
plt.plot(used_diffs, wr)
plt.xlabel('Winning team\'s kill difference at 20 mins')
plt.ylabel('Winrate')
plt.title('Winrate based on the winning team\'s kill difference at 20 mins')

A single lane's effect on the outcome of a game¶

Another condition that people claim makes a game unwinnable is when one lane is ahead, even if it is just one enemy player that's ahead out of the 5, they will call for a surrender vote. The phrase "Top gap" comes to mind (which refers to a gap in skill between the two top laners which caused the loss/win). To see how righteous this claim is, I will analyze the number of games won when each lane is ahead by x kills over time.

See Below the graphs for analysis and explanation

In [44]:
##This is a helper function that maps all of the potential keys in the keys list to their corresponding value in dictionary
##d. This returns a list of those values
def val_list(d, keys):
    ret = []
    for k in keys:
        ret.append(d[k])
    return ret

##Another helper function used in analyzing the event dataframes. In order to filter a dataframe based on a column, you

## if a certain player assisted in any of the rowas of column assist_list (a list of player lists)
def did_player_assist(assist_list, player):
    ret = []
    for assists in assist_list:
        ret.append(player in assists)
    return ret

Okay, that was a lot of graphs, but bear with me. There are groups of three graphs at a time. Each group is seperated by 10 minutes.

  • The first graph in a group shows the number of games won when a laner (distinguished by their line color) is ahead by x kills at t minutes (specefied in the title of the graph). This was done to see if any one laner could get away with a higher winrate than other lanes even if they lose to their opponent (in kills). For example If bot lane's graph is abve the rest of the lanes' graphs when the kill difference is negative, we could conclude that bot lane would not have as much of an impact on the outcome of the game as they lost more than the other lanes, but still won the game.
  • The second graph in a set shows the number of games won when a laner has x more deaths than their lane opponent at time t. This was done because a laner may benefit their own team by having more kills than their opponent, but that benefit may be overshadowed if that laner died more times to the enemy team. For example, in a game, the two junglers may have the scores 4/10/~ and 1/1/~ (in K/D/A format). If we look at the first graph (which only counts kills), we may think that the first jungler is benefitting their team more than the second jungler. However, considering the deaths of both junglers, the first jungler would have benefitted the enemy team by dying to them more often than he benefitted his own team by getting kills. In other words, the second jungler is obviously doing better. If a lane's graph falls above the other lanes' graphs when the death difference is positive, then it could be reasoned that the lane would be able to die more yet win more than the other lanes with the same death disparities.
  • The last graph shows how many games are won when a laner has x more participation in their team's kills than Their Team's average kill participation at time t. Kill participation is defined as the fraction number of kills that you participated in over the number of kills your team has. For instance, if your team has 4 kills total, and you only have 1, your kill participation would be 1/4. This was done to see if a team could lose more due to a single lane's bad performance. If a lane is not participating in the fights with the rest of the team, will that affect the outcome of the game?

When in doubt, just look at the title of the graph and it should be self-explanatory

10 Minutes¶

Here, there wasn't much surprise. 10 minutes into the game is still considered the early game, so there is a lot of time for a team to fix any errors in the remainder of the game. Every lane's pull on the outcome of the game appears to be equal for the most part

20 Minutes¶

Here, we start to see some outliers. All lane's kill difference appears to affect the outcome evenly, as does a lane's kill participation. However, Top lane's graph falls noticeably out of line with the other lanes when it comes to having more deaths than the enemy laner. It would appear that a top laner could die much more than his opponent and win more games than another laner dying the same amount

30 Minutes¶

Kill disparity appears to be even as always, but now, death disparity effect in the top lane has shifted even further from the rest of the lanes, and the kill participation graph seems to show a similar (yet smaller shift). It looks like the top lane may be able to participate in fights less than other laners and still win.

40 Minutes¶

There isn't much change between the 30 minute graphs and the 40 minute graphs. They show the same general trends I have been discussing for the other timeframes. This is most likely because fewer games last for 40 minutes than 30 minutes. If a game ends before 40 minutes, the statistics of the players won't change anymore to affect the outcome of the game, so the graphs will remain where they were at the last threshold. There will still be some minor changes from the few games that last to 40 the 40 minute mark and beyond

Does top lane have to do well to win? Why are the graphs showing that top lane can die more and participate in fights less and still win? I would have to crunch some more data, but if I had to guess, I would say that this discrepancy is due to common strategies with top laners. In many games, top laners are encouraged to avoid highly-contested areas of the map in favor of 'split pushing' or constantly threatening structures far away from a contested area to draw attention away from their team. For instance, if both teams are sending most of their players to the bottom side of the map to compete for a resource, one team may send their top laner to the opposite side of the map to threaten a turret or other enemy structure there. This forces the enemy team into a dilemma. Will they leave the hot zone to defend their base but give up the resource? Or will they stay and fight for the resource, but lose portions of their base to the split pushing top laner?

This would explain the excess of deaths and the lack of kill participation. If the top laner is away from the hot zone, they won't participate in any kills made there, but if the enemy team elects to defend their base, the top laner would often die during the defense, but his team would benefit from obtaining the resource that the enemy team gave up to defend their base.

I will save this analysis for another time.

Conclusion¶

I entered this project aiming to find out if people were justified in claiming that a game was unwinnable under certain circumstances in the early game. I found that for many of the common 'unwinnable conditions', the winrate for both teams was high enough to warrant continued effort.

  • First Blood ~55/45 % advantage
  • First Dragon ~60/40 % advantage
  • First Tower ~60/40% advantage
  • First Herald ~60/40% advantage
  • First Mythic Item ~60/40% advantage
  • First Baron ~80/20% advantage (All calculated over 500 randomly sampled games)

In other words, most of these unwinnable conditions Are more winnable than people expect

I also looked at the effects of changing kill difference between teams at 20 minutes on winrate. As it turns out, the state of the game at 20 minutes often does determine the outcome of the game. It appears that after a kill defecit of 10, your winrate is down to about 20%, and gets worse from there. At this point, the justification for an 'unwinnable game' based on the score is going to depend on how optimistic you are about low winrates. If your expected chance of winning is 20% at a certain point in the game, are you willing to put forth the effort to win 1/5 of the games with those conditions? For me, the answer is always yes. I don't expect, nor would I tell people to expect to win under those circumstances, but if you're playing a large number of games in a ranked setting for the purposes of climbing the ranked ladder, taking those 1/5 games will slowly add up over time, and hypothetically your rank should be higher than if you threw those chances away. Something about the law of gross numbers and some-such.

I also looked at the claims that one lane is more/less important to the outcome of a game based on a few factors throughout the game. The factors I checked were by no means exhaustive, but based on the factors I chose, I saw no evidence to a systematic advantage that one lane has over the others.

If you disagree with any of the observations I made, that's great! I'm not perfect, but I've also shown you the tools necessary to gather enough data (or the same data) to dispute any of my claims. If this notebook is successful, hopefully you will know how to use them too :)
